  Two new ideas discovered this session — need implementation plans

  Idea 1: Stochastic Markov opponent model (~100ms compute budget)

  The root cause of v3's oracle catastrophe was argmax over opponent's orbit_lite scores. The fix: replace with a Boltzmann/softmax distribution:

  P(opp attacks planet j | GS1) ∝ exp(score_j / τ)

  Then 2-ply value becomes an expectation over the opponent distribution, not a minimax:

  EV(W1) = Σ_j  P(R1_j | GS1)  ×  competitive_score(W1 + R1_j)

  This is a proper 2-step Markov chain (Bellman equation for 2-player MDP). Temperature τ → 0 is the oracle disaster; τ → ∞ is random; τ optimal matches real opponent
  concentration. Needs τ tuned, probably via Optuna (50 trials × 10 games).

  Critically: with the stochastic model, there's no need for the clears_floor filter — EV(W1) naturally scores losing attacks near zero. We now have ~192 viable (src, tgt)
  pairs to evaluate instead of 0–4. The candidate pool problem is solved.

  Compute: 10 candidates × (1 orbit_lite opp distribution call ~5ms + top-5 opp moves × 1ms) = ~100ms. Well within the ~900ms available budget.

  Idea 2: Periodic orbit timing — "WHEN to attack, not just WHETHER" (~negligible extra compute)

  Currently schmeekler asks "is attacking planet X profitable RIGHT NOW?" and passes if not. It has no look-ahead on when planet X will be cheapest to capture.

  Planets orbit the sun with period ~40–80 steps. At different points in the orbit, the same planet costs different amounts to capture (distance from our nearest source
  varies → floor varies → ships needed varies).

  Proposal: for each target planet in the shortlist, scan the next 150 steps (alive_by_step is already computed) to find the minimum capture floor and the step at which it
  occurs. If min floor occurs in T_future steps and current floor is 2× that, output a "hold" signal — suppress attacking now, accumulate garrison, attack at the optimal
  window.

  Compute cost: negligible — floor is already computed for K_eta steps. Just scan forward rather than reading only the arrival-time index.

  This is completely orthogonal to the stochastic opponent model and could be implemented independently. Ted was enthusiastic about this one specifically.

